# TSX best principles

- DRY: avoid copy/paste; extract shared logic into a helper only when it meaningfully reduces duplication (used by more than one consumer) AND it is genuinely general-purpose (not tied to one component/feature/domain).
  - Keep a general-purpose utility module/file (e.g. `util.ts`/`utils.ts`) for generic helpers shared across multiple components.
  - For component/domain-specific constants and behavior, keep them in the component file.
  - Example: graph size ratio constants should stay in `ChartGrid.tsx` (or wherever they are truly chart-specific), not be moved into a generic `util.ts`/`utils.ts` module.
- Red flag for over-extraction: if moving something into a shared helper makes edits harder (e.g. awkward imports/names or you’re encoding chart/export-specific semantics into `util.ts`), keep it local instead.
- Prefer reuse over “parallel implementations” of the same idea in different files.
- Remove unused code:
  - Delete unused imports, variables, parameters, functions, and dead branches.
  - Remove unused constants/types and any code that becomes unreachable after your changes.
- If you need to keep code temporarily, prefer a clear `TODO` with the reason (not commented-out blocks) and keep it minimal.
